[15:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work. It essentially, you know, generates a token and then follows it up. You know, it\'s a prediction engine. It follows it up with the next likely token. And obviously, as those tokens continue to build up and context builds up, we get to the point of'

[15:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hallucinations. Meanwhile, on the image side of things, well, hallucinations, oddly, I mean, that\'s kind of how they work. I\'m not going to go long on this here, but in case you\'re not aware, most image generators generally begin with a'

[16:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cloud burst of static and then slowly hallucinate out what your prompt is from that static. So, Mercury Two from Inception Labs kind of flips that on its head and asks like, well, you know, what if there was a language model that uh'

[16:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that essentially worked a little bit more like an image model. So, I\'m not going to go too heavy on the how it works, but you know, obviously, the criticism of LLMs being a fancy autocomplete, well, the the diffusion method is an idea that where it'

[16:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'essentially begins with a fully masked like burst of static masked output and then refines all of that in parallel over like denoising steps like we do with images. And apparently, this method'

